nm-to-m-nanometers-to-meters-conversion-1024x683.png" alt=3D"nm to m - nano=
meters to meters conversion" class=3D"wp-image-97984 lazyloaded"></a><figca=
ption class=3D"wp-element-caption">The nm to m (nanometers to meters) conve=
rsion is a simple matter of either multiplication or division. The only tri=
cky part is working with exponents.</figcaption></figure><p>The nm to m or =
nanometers to meters conversion is common in science, particularly when you=
 deal with wavelengths of light or tiny objects like atoms and molecules. O=
ne nanometer (American) or nanometre (international) is 10<sup>-9</sup> met=
ers or 1/1,000,000,000 meters. In other words, a nanometer is one-billionth=
 of a meter. The conversion is easy, although you <a href=3D"https://scienc=
enotes.org/exponent-rules-and-examples/">work with exponents</a>. Here=E2=
=80=99s what you do, along with examples of the conversion.</p><h3 class=3D=
"wp-block-heading">nm to m Conversion Factor</h3><ul style=3D"background-co=
lor:#ffcaca" class=3D"wp-block-list has-background"><li><strong>1 m =3D 10<=
sup>9</sup> nm =3D 1,000,000,000 nm</strong></li><li><strong>1 nm =3D 10<su=
p>-9</sup> m =3D 0.000000001 m</strong></li></ul><p>Rewriting the conversio=
n factor as a formula, you get:<div id=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-987f-862e4=
c9b7eb0_1" class=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-987f-862e4c9b7eb0 mmt-primary" s=
tyle=3D"display: block;"><div id=3D"mmt-178c34ae-e668-46a3-987f-862e4c9b7eb=
0_1_zone" style=3D"visibility: visible !important;"></div></div></p><p>dist=
ance in meters =3D distance in nanometers x 10<sup>-9</sup> =3D distance in=
 nanometers / 10<sup>9</sup></p><p>It does not matter which version of the =
formula you use.</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Convert Nanometer=
s to Meters (nm to m)</h3><ul class=3D"wp-block-list"><li>Convert nanometer=
s to meters by multiplying nanometers by 10<sup>-9</sup> (0.000000001) or b=
y dividing by 10<sup>9</sup> (1000000000).</li><li>If the idea of entering =
the exponents into your calculator intimidates you, just use this simple me=
thod of working with exponents. Convert nm to m by subtracting 9 from the e=
xponent.</li><li>This is the same as moving the decimal point 9 spaces to t=
he left.</li></ul><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">nm to m (Nanometers to Met=
ers) Example Problem</h3><p>For example, a helium-neon (red) laser has a wa=
velength of 632.8 nanometers. Convert this into meters.</p><p>Solve the pro=
blem by setting it up so the nanometers cancel out, leaving meters:</p><p>d=
istance in m =3D (distance in nm) x (1 m/10<sup>9</sup>&nbsp;nm)<br>Note: 1=
/10<sup>9</sup>&nbsp;=3D 10<sup>-9</sup><br>distance in m =3D (632.8 x 10<s=
up>-9</sup>) m<br>distance in m =3D 6.328 x 10<sup>-7</sup>&nbsp;m<br><br>6=
32.8 nanometers equals 6.328 x 10<sup>-7</sup>&nbsp;meters.</p><p>You get t=
he same answer by moving the decimal point 9 spaces to the left:</p><p>632.=
8 =3D 0.0000006328 m =3D 6.328 x 10<sup>-7</sup></p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-h=
eading">How to Convert Meters to Nanometers (m to nm)</h3><ul class=3D"wp-b=
lock-list"><li>Convert meters to nanometers (m to nm) by dividing meters by=
 10<sup>-9</sup> or multiplying by 10<sup>9</sup>.</li><li>Alternatively, c=
onvert m to by writing the value in meters in <a href=3D"https://sciencenot=
es.org/scientific-notation-working-with-exponents/">scientific notation</a>=
 and adding 9 to the exponent.</li><li>This is the same as moving the decim=
al point 9 spaces to the right.</li></ul><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">m t=
o nm (Meters to Nanometers) Example Problem</h3><p>For example, the longest=
 wavelength of <a href=3D"https://sciencenotes.org/visible-light-spectrum-w=
avelengths-and-colors/">visible light</a> most people see is red that is ne=
arly <a href=3D"https://sciencenotes.org/infrared-light-infrared-radiation/=
">infrared</a>. The wavelength of this light is 7 x 10<sup>-7</sup>&nbsp;me=
ters. What is this wavelength in nanometers?</p><p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_1-0-=
12">length in nm =3D (length in m) x (10<sup>9</sup>&nbsp;nm/m)</p><p id=3D=
"mntl-sc-block_1-0-14">The meters <a href=3D"https://sciencenotes.org/si-ba=
se-units/">unit</a> cancels out, leaving nm.</p><p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_1-0-=
16">length in nm =3D (7 x 10<sup>-7</sup>) x (10<sup>9</sup>) nm</p><p id=
=3D"mntl-sc-block_1-0-18">or, you could write this as:</p><p id=3D"mntl-sc-=
block_1-0-20">length in nm =3D (7 x 10<sup>-7</sup>) x (1 x 10<sup>9</sup>)=
 nm</p><p id=3D"mntl-sc-block_1-0-22">When you multiply powers of 10, just =
add the exponents. In this case, you add -7 to 9, which gives you 2:</p><p =
id=3D"mntl-sc-block_1-0-24">length of red light in nm =3D 7 x 10<sup>2</sup=
>&nbsp;nm =3D 700 nm</p><h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">References</h3><ul c=
